## Core Engagement Loop

```
Open app → Dashboard (due count + practice history) → Practice (2-3 min) → See what you practised → Decide what's next or stop
```

The loop centres on the activity and its real output. The streak calendar is a
passive record of consistency, not the payoff. The payoff is the practice itself
and the competence signals that emerge from it over time.

## Motivation Design

The app's engagement philosophy follows Self-Determination Theory. Every feedback
moment is evaluated on two axes:

1. **Informational vs controlling.** The app describes what happened ("You practised
   14 forms in 4 minutes"). It does not evaluate the user ("Great job!") or direct
   their behaviour ("Keep going!"). The user decides how to feel about their session.

2. **Internal vs external locus.** The user practises because the activity itself
   is valuable to them. The app reflects their progress honestly but never becomes
   the reason they practise. If you removed every feedback mechanic and the user
   would still practise, the design is working.

### User stage context

The primary user is Stage 1 (initiation) — building the habit from scratch. Recall
is poor, understanding is developing, reference material is heavily relied upon.
External scaffolding is appropriate and necessary at this stage: reminders, due
counts, and consistency tracking all serve the goal of getting enough repetitions
for the behaviour to start becoming automatic. But the *form* of that scaffolding
matters — it should be informational, never controlling.

<hooks>
<hook name="due-count" location="dashboard" mechanism="informational">
Shows number of items due for review with time estimate. Factual: "12 items (~3 min)".
No urgency framing, no FOMO language. The count is useful information, not pressure.
</hook>
<hook name="practice-calendar" location="dashboard" mechanism="informational">
Weekly grid showing practice days. A passive record of consistency — the user can
see their pattern without the app evaluating it. No streak counter, no "X days!"
label. The calendar speaks for itself.
</hook>
<hook name="short-sessions" location="practice" mechanism="low-friction">
2-3 minute sessions lower the activation threshold. The user can always do "just
one drill." Starting is the hard part; most users continue once they begin.
</hook>
<hook name="auto-advance" location="speed-drill" mechanism="flow-state">
Correct answers auto-advance, maintaining momentum. Flow produces its own
dopamine — don't interrupt it with celebrations.
</hook>
<hook name="push-notifications" location="system" mechanism="external-prompt">
Daily reminders for first 2 weeks, tapering to every-other-day by week 3.
Content is informational: "Your Greek is waiting" not "Don't break your streak!"
Includes one-tap "Not today" that triggers no guilt. Around day 14, offer:
"You seem to have this — want fewer reminders?"
</hook>
<hook name="lapsed-user-recovery" location="dashboard" mechanism="reduced-friction">
Users returning after 7+ days see warm, no-guilt messaging. "Your vocabulary is
still here." For large queues (15+ items): "Just 5 items" as default tiny action.
After longer gaps: show what they'd built before the break, offer a lighter
re-entry session. Never reset or penalise progress.
</hook>
<hook name="post-session-acknowledgement" location="drill-summary" mechanism="informational">
Describes what happened: items practised, time spent, which items took the most
effort. No person-praise ("You're amazing!"), no evaluation ("Great session!").
When sessions are hard, reframe the struggle: "These 3 forms took the most effort.
That's where durable learning happens." Offer a fork: 2-3 genuinely different next
steps as low-key links, not one dominant CTA.
</hook>
<hook name="consistency-milestones" location="dashboard" mechanism="informational">
Quiet inline text at natural breakpoints. "You've been practising for a week."
Period. No confetti, no modal, no forced interaction. The user feels whatever they
feel about it without the app directing the emotion. These appear as part of the
normal dashboard flow, not as interruptions.
</hook>
<hook name="evening-reminder" location="system" mechanism="external-prompt">
Push notification at 8pm UTC for users who haven't practised today (first few
weeks only). Content: "Your review queue has X items" — factual, no streak
mention, no loss framing. Tapers as the habit forms.
</hook>
</hooks>

### Anti-patterns to avoid

These are explicitly rejected, regardless of how effective they appear short-term:

| Pattern | Why it fails |
|---------|-------------|
| "Don't lose your streak!" | Loss framing is controlling. Creates anxiety, not motivation. Missing a day doesn't impact habit formation (Lally). |
| Confetti / particle celebrations | Habituates within days, interrupts flow, positions app as judge. |
| Modal celebration dialogs | Blocks autonomy, forces interaction, app as authority. |
| "You're amazing!" / "Great job!" | Person-praise creates fixed mindset (Dweck). App is judging identity, not describing action. |
| Same celebration for easy and hard | Disconnects feedback from reality. User detects the dishonesty. |
| XP / points for completion | Expected tangible reward undermines intrinsic motivation. User optimises for points, not learning. |

### Good patterns to use

| Pattern | Why it works |
|---------|-------------|
| Acknowledge, don't praise | "You practised 14 forms." Informational, user retains agency. |
| Tiny default action | "Review 1 card" or "Just 5 items." Crosses activation threshold without requiring motivation. |
| The fork | 2-3 genuinely different next steps. User directs their own path. |
| Struggle reframe | "These took the most effort. That's where lasting learning happens." Reframes difficulty as productive. |
| Reward recovery | After a lapse: welcome back warmly, no guilt, show what's waiting. |
| Domain bridge (sparingly) | "The tense you just practised is how news articles are written." Real-world connection. Once a week max. |

### Stage progression notes

As the user accumulates practice data (weeks 3-10), introduce:
- **The delta:** Self-comparison over time. "These forms took 4 min today. Last week: 12."
  Only show when the data tells a real story. This is the strongest competence signal.
- **Self-set targets:** "You've been doing about 10 minutes. Want to set that as your target?"
  Let them adjust freely, no penalty for falling short.
- **Desirable difficulty:** Increase spacing, interleave topics. Acknowledge when it's harder:
  "This drill mixes tenses. Mixing is harder but produces more lasting memory."

## Current Implementation

<features>
<feature name="streak-freeze" status="implemented">
<current>Streak freeze system with auto-activation</current>
<details>
- Earn 1 freeze per 7 consecutive days (max 3)
- Auto-activates on missed day
- 24h cooldown between freeze uses
- Dashboard shows freeze count and status
- Uses protective framing: "Freeze saved your streak" (not loss framing)
</details>
<motivation-note>Freeze mechanic is acceptable scaffolding at Stage 1. It reduces
anxiety about missed days without loss-framing. The framing matters: "miss a day,
keep your streak" is protective; "don't lose your streak" is controlling.</motivation-note>
</feature>
<feature name="evening-reminder" status="implemented">
<current>Push notification at 8pm UTC for users who haven't practised</current>
<details>
- Cron trigger in wrangler.toml (0 20 * * *)
- Checks users with active streaks who haven't practised today
</details>
<motivation-note>Appropriate at Stage 1 but needs reframing. Current copy "Don't
lose your X-day streak!" is loss-framed — replace with informational: "Your review
queue has X items." Should taper after week 3 as the habit forms.</motivation-note>
</feature>
<feature name="milestones" status="needs-rework">
<current>Celebration modal at 7, 30, 100, 365 days with confetti</current>
<details>
- MilestoneCelebration component shows confetti + message
- Persisted to milestonesAchieved table via /api/milestones
- Only shows once per milestone per user
</details>
<motivation-note>Confetti + modal combines two universal anti-patterns. Replace with
quiet inline text on dashboard: "You've been practising for a week." No modal, no
confetti, no forced interaction. Persist the milestone data (useful for analytics)
but change the presentation.</motivation-note>
</feature>
<feature name="post-session-messages" status="needs-rework">
<current>Variable encouragement messages with icons based on accuracy</current>
<details>
- Trophy/Flame/Sparkles icons tiered by accuracy
- Messages like "You're on fire!", "Great session!", "You showed up — that's what matters!"
</details>
<motivation-note>Person-praise and app-as-judge. Replace with informational
acknowledgement: describe what happened (items practised, time, effort distribution),
offer the fork (2-3 next steps), and when sessions were hard, use the struggle
reframe instead of hollow encouragement.</motivation-note>
</feature>
<feature name="tomorrow-hook" status="implemented">
<current>Dashboard shows "Tomorrow: X items" with calendar icon</current>
<motivation-note>Informational — shows what's coming without pressure. Acceptable
as passive data the user can glance at.</motivation-note>
</feature>
</features>

## Data Tables

<tables>
<table name="users">User accounts (id, code, username, displayName, passwordHash, freezeCount, lastFreezeUsedAt, freezeUsedForDate, consecutiveDaysAtEarn)</table>
<table name="passkeys">WebAuthn credentials (userId, credentialId, publicKey, counter, transports, deviceType, backedUp, lastUsedAt)</table>
<table name="authChallenges">WebAuthn challenge storage (challenge, type, userId, expiresAt) - 5min TTL</table>
<table name="vocabulary">All Greek words/phrases (greekText, englishTranslation, wordType, gender, metadata, declensionPattern)</table>
<table name="tags">Vocabulary categorisation (slug, name, description)</table>
<table name="tagSections">UI display organisation (tagId, section, displayOrder)</table>
<table name="vocabularyTags">Many-to-many vocab↔tag join table</table>
<table name="verbDetails">Verb metadata (conjugationFamily, stems, isSuppletive, notes)</table>
<table name="verbConjugations">Full verb paradigms by tense (vocabId, tense, person, form)</table>
<table name="verbImperatives">Imperative forms (vocabId, aspect, number, form)</table>
<table name="practiceSessions">Session metadata (userId, sessionType, category, timestamps)</table>
<table name="practiceAttempts">Practice history (sessionId, vocabId, isCorrect, timeTaken)</table>
<table name="weakAreas">Pattern-based weak spots (userId, areaType, identifier, errorCount)</table>
<table name="vocabularySkills">SRS state per user per word (easeFactor, intervalDays, reviewCount, nextReviewAt)</table>
<table name="pushSubscriptions">Push notification endpoints (userId, endpoint, keys)</table>
<table name="milestonesAchieved">Milestone celebrations shown (userId, milestoneType, achievedAt)</table>
</tables>

## User State

- Session in localStorage (`greek-authenticated-user`) as JSON: `{userId, username}`
- Authentication via username/password or WebAuthn passkey
- Existing users without passwords prompted to set one on first login
- Registration creates new account with password, optional passkey setup

